Part 1 - Getting Started [1 marks]¶

Ailerons are small hinged sections on the outboard portion of a wing used to control the roll of an airplane. In this project, we are going to design a controller to manage the ailerons of an aircraft based on supervised learning.

The following dataset contains 13750 instances, where each instance is a set of 40 features describing the airplane's status. Our goal is to use these features to predict the Goal column, which is a command that our controller should issue. We will make our predictions by implementing linear regression.

Q: Epoch vs Iteration¶

The difference is on the unit:

  • Epoch: one epoch is when an entire dataset is passed
  • Iteration: iterations are the number of batches needed to complete one epoch

Part 2 - Linear Regression Using Direct Solution [1 marks]¶

Implement the direct solution of the linear regression problem on the training set. [0.5]

Note: You should use scipy.linalg.inv to perform the matrix inversion, as numpy.linalg.inv may cause numerical issues.

Report the root-mean-square error (RMSE) for both the training and validation sets. [0.5]

You may use mean_squared_error from Sklearn for computing the RMSE.

In [8]:
# direct solution
# analytical solution
W = np.dot(np.linalg.inv(np.dot(X_train.T, X_train)), np.dot(X_train.T, y_train))

# prediction
y_train_pred = np.dot(X_train, W)
y_val_pred = np.dot(X_val, W)

def rmse(y_pred_, y_):
    return np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_, y_pred_))

print('Training RMSE:', rmse(y_train_pred, y_train))
print('Validation RMSE:', rmse(y_val_pred, y_val))

Part 3 - Full Batch Gradient Descent [2 marks]¶

We will now implement a "full batch" gradient descent algorithm and record the training time for our model. Recall that the full batch gradient descent is, $$w_t = w_{t-1} - \alpha~g_t$$ where $\alpha$ is the learning rate and $g_t$ is your gradient, computed on the entire data.

Here are the steps for this part:

  • Implement gradient descent for linear regression using a fixed learning rate of $\alpha= 0.01$, and iterate until your model's validation RMSE converges.

    We consider the gradient descent as having converged when RMSE on the validation set using gradient descent satisfies:

    $$ RMSE_\text{GD} \leq 1.001 \times RMSE_\text{Direct Solution}$$

    where $RMSE_\text{Direct Solution}$ is the RMSE on the validation set using the direct solution that you have calculated in the previous part.

    We refer to the quantity $RMSE_\text{Direct Solution}\times 1.001$ as the convergence threshold (CT).

  • Record the training time (from the first iteration until convergence) using the time.time() function. Be sure to compute the gradients yourself! Take a look at the code provided in the tutorial. [0.5]

  • Plot the training RMSE and the validation RMSE vs. epoch on the same figure. [0.5]

  • Comment on overfitting/underfitting by observing the training and validation RMSE [1]

Hint: Initialize your weights with small random numbers (<$0.001$)

In [15]:
## GD Script -- Sample code in tutorial! ##
def gradient_descent_full_batch(X_train_, y_train_, X_val_, y_val_,
                                learning_rate=0.01, rmse_direct= rmse(y_val_pred, y_val)):
    start_time = time.time() ## Records current time
    W_ = np.random.random(X_train_.shape[1])/1000 ### initial random weights
    lr_ = learning_rate
    rmse_val_array_ = []
    rmse_train_array_ = []

    # initial validate value
    y_val_pred_ = np.dot(X_val_, W_.T)
    rmse_val_array_.append(rmse(y_val_pred_, y_val_))

    # for the rest epoch
    while rmse_val_array_[-1] > 1.001 * rmse_direct:
        # validation update
        y_val_pred_ = np.dot(X_val_, W_.T)
        rmse_val_array_.append(rmse(y_val_pred_, y_val_))
        # training update
        y_train_pred_ = np.dot(X_train_, W_.T)
        rmse_train_array_.append(rmse(y_train_pred_, y_train_))
        # update gradient
        gradient_ = (1/len(y_train_pred_) * np.dot(X_train_.T, (y_train_pred_ - y_train_)))
        W_ = W_ - lr_ * gradient_ ### weight update

    # remove the initial
    rmse_val_array_.pop(0)
    # plot
    plt.figure(figsize=(16, 9))
    plt.plot(range(100), rmse_train_array_[:100], label='Training')
    plt.plot(range(100), rmse_val_array_[:100], label='Validation')
    plt.xlabel("Epoch", fontsize=14)
    plt.ylabel("RMSE", fontsize=14)
    plt.title('Full Batch Gradient Descent Iteration', fontsize=16)
    plt.legend(fontsize=14)
    print("--- Total Training Time: %s (s) ---" % (time.time() - start_time))

Part 4 - Mini-batch and Stochastic Gradient Descent [4 marks]¶

Write a function that performs mini-batch gradient descent until the convergence threshold (CT) is reached. [1]

The inputs of that function are:

  • Input data (training/validation), Batch size, Learning Rate, Convergence Threshold (CT)

Your function will return the following arrays:

  • The final weights after training.
  • The training RMSE at each epoch.
  • The validation RMSE at each epoch.
  • An array that has the elapsed time from the start of the training process to the end of each epoch (e.g., if each epoch takes exactly 2 seconds, the array would look like: [2 4 6 8 ...]).

Notes:

  • For certain batch sizes, GD might not converge to a solution. For that reason, you need to check the RMSE of the validation/training set at each epoch, and if it's getting larger and larger, you should stop the training for that case (the design is up to you!).
  • CT will help you to know when your model is converged.
  • Important: after each epoch, you need to shuffle the entire training set. This ensures that new mini-batches are selected for every epoch. Hint: use np.random.permutation.

Let's now use the function to investigate the effect of batch size on convergence. When the batch size is 1, we call that stochastic gradient descent. When the batch size equals the # of training data, it is full-batch (i.e., all data points are used at every iteration). Anywhere in between is mini-batch (we use some data).

  • Sweep different values for the mini-batch size (at least 5 values that converge), each time using a learning rate of $\alpha= 0.01$. Hint: Try batch sizes that are powers of two (e.g., 2,4,8,16,32,64,128...). These batch sizes fit better on the hardware and may achieve higher performance. [0.5]

def gradient_descent_mini_batch(X_train_, y_train_, X_val_, y_val_,
                                batch_size_power2, learning_rate=0.01, threshold=rmse(y_val_pred, y_val)):

    W_ = np.random.random(X_train_.shape[1])/1000 ### initial random weights
    lr_ = learning_rate
    rmse_val_array_ = []
    rmse_train_array_ = []
    process_time_array_ = []
    batch_size = 2**batch_size_power2
    flag_converge = True
    c_diverge = 8

    # initial validate value
    y_val_pred_ = np.dot(X_val_, W_.T)
    rmse_val_array_.append(rmse(y_val_pred_, y_val_))

    # records current time
    start_time = time.time()

    # for the rest epoch
    while rmse_val_array_[-1] > 1.001 * threshold and flag_converge:
        # validation update
        y_val_pred_ = np.dot(X_val_, W_.T)
        rmse_val = rmse(y_val_pred_, y_val_)
        rmse_val_array_.append(rmse_val)

        # check diverge
        if len(rmse_val_array_) > c_diverge:
            rmse_check_ = rmse_val_array_[-c_diverge:]
            if all([rmse_check_[-r] > rmse_check_[-(r+1)]
                    for r in range(1,len(rmse_check_))]):
                print('Diverge at Batch Size = %d'%(2**batch_size_power2))
                flag_converge = False

        # training update
        y_train_pred_ = np.dot(X_train_, W_.T)
        rmse_train = rmse(y_train_pred_, y_train_)
        rmse_train_array_.append(rmse_train)

        # batch gradient update
        for b in range(0, X_train_.shape[0], batch_size):
            X_batch = X_train_[b:b + batch_size]
            y_batch = y_train_[b:b + batch_size]
            y_pred_batch = np.dot(X_batch, W_.T)
            gradient_ = (1/len(y_pred_batch) * np.dot(X_batch.T, (y_pred_batch - y_batch)))
            W_ = W_ - lr_ * gradient_

        # add time
        process_time_array_.append(time.time() - start_time)

        # shuffle X
        rand = list(np.random.permutation(X_train_.shape[0]))
        X_train_ = X_train_[rand]
        y_train_ = y_train_[rand]

    # remove the initial
    rmse_val_array_.pop(0)

    return W_, rmse_train_array_, rmse_val_array_, process_time_array_, flag_converge

Comment¶

The Epoch vs RMSE and Time vs RMSE have similar results, the batch size of 64 has some ups and downs with the training RMSE value, but still be able to converge at the end.

To deal with this kind of fluctuation, I set a convergence index(c_diverge) that check the condition of recent 8(my setting) training RMSEs, and if one of them is decreasing, the SGD will still operate. Otherwise, the model diverges.

After batch size = 64, all other batch sizes converge smoothly, and no many difference with training and validation curves. With increase of the batch size, the curves become more rounded and the RMSE drop slower.

From the Time vs Batch Size plot, we can conclude: in general, larger the batch size, longer the training time, but there is a drop at batch size = 256. The fastest converge time is obtained by the one with the smallest converged batch size, which is 64.

    plt.xlabel("Epoch", fontsize=14)
    plt.ylabel("RMSE", fontsize=14)
    plt.title('Mini Batch Gradient Descent Iteration: Epoch vs RMSE', fontsize=16)
    plt.legend(fontsize=14)

    # plot rmse vs time
    plt.subplot(2,1,2)
    plt.plot(process_time_array, rmse_train_array, label='Train at LR = %.3f' % lr)
    plt.plot(process_time_array, rmse_val_array, ls='--', label='Test at LR = %.3f' % lr)
    plt.xlabel("Time", fontsize=14)
    plt.ylabel("RMSE", fontsize=14)
    plt.title('Mini Batch Gradient Descent Iteration: Time vs RMSE', fontsize=16)
    plt.legend(fontsize=14)
plt.show()

Comment¶

Since the linear model with mini batch SGD can perform a good result(all converges), the optimization is on the train time, we find out large learning rate with small batch size may have issue to converge. Therefore, we firstly find the optimized batch size 64, with the fastest speed.

Then we use the size 64 to test 10 different small learning rate, and find out at lr = 0.008, the time is the shortest. Therefore, the best model is found.

The best model perform really well on the testing set, two curves drop almost at the same rate, with less than 10 epoch and 0.025 seconds.

For the final performance on task of managing ailerons of an aircraft, the model found CurPitch, inputs Climb Rate, AbsRoll, SeTime5 and some other SeTimes as the key features with testing RMSE= 0.0001712.

Part 7 - Getting started with GitHub [3 marks]¶

This final part of the project assignment is to be completed independently of Parts 1 - 6. In this part you will be completing some additional coding tasks using a different dataset and submitting your results on GitHub. To access this part of the assignment and upload your answers, you will need to use GitHub. Please complete the following step-by-step instructions:

  1. Create a GitHub account and install git for Windows or Mac:

    • https://git-scm.com/download/win
    • https://git-scm.com/download/mac

  2. Open this link: https://classroom.github.com/a/ZC8Petsq to create your assignment repository in GitHub. You should get a link similar to:

    https://github.com/APS-1070-2021/f22-project4-git-*********

    This private repository to get this part questions and upload your answers. Copy this link to the text box below to be graded for this part.

  1. Open Git Bash, the app you downloaded in step 0, and set your Email and username by:

    git config --global user.email “<your-GitHub-email>”
git config --global user.name “<your-GitHub-username>”

  2. Create a folder for the course on your computer and cd to that. cd means Change Directory. For example, on a Windows machine, where I have a folder on "C:\aps1070":

    cd c:aps1070

  3. Get your assignment by the link you got in step 1:

    git clone https://github.com/APS-1070-2021/f22-project4-git-*********

    If this is the first time you are using Git Bash, it will ask you to sign in on GitHub via your browser.

  4. A new folder should be created in your directory similar to:

    C:\aps1070\f22-project4-git-********

    This folder has an ipynb notebook which you need to manually upload to colab and answer its questions.

  5. After you finished working on this notebook, download the notebook from colab and move it to the directory in step 5.

  6. Replace the old notebook with the new one that has your answers. Make sure your completed notebook has the same name as the original notebook you downloaded.

  7. To submit your work, follow:

    cd <your assignment folder>
git add F22_Project_4_git.ipynb
git commit -m “Final Submission”
git push

    If you had any problem with pushing your work on GitHub you can try one of following commands:

    git push --force
or 
git push origin HEAD:main

  8. Make sure your submission is ready for grading. Open the private repository link in your browser and make sure you can see your final submission with your latest changes there. Only you and the teaching team can open that link.
